ported by the source. However, I notice the knowledge file uses \"設計コンセプト\" while the source describes the actual capabilities that enable long-term reliable use rather than explicitly naming it as a design concept—I should be more careful about distinguishing between what's explicitly stated versus what's inferred.\n\nMoving through the second section, the emphasis on testability and the specific testing mechanisms like drivers, mocks, and automated test frameworks all check out. For the third section, I'm confirming the framework components, the middleware adapters for commonly used tools, and the provision of an environment for quick onboarding are all present in the source material.\n\nNow I'm looking at the structure of the document itself. The RST formatting uses delimiter lines above and below text to mark hierarchy levels, so what appeared as 6 headings in the automated check is actually just the formatting convention—there's really 1 document title and 3 section headings, which matches the 3 knowledge sections perfectly.\n\nMoving on to verify the hints are complete for each section: Robustness covers the key terms around stability and security, while Testability includes the relevant testing-related vocabulary.\n\nThe main issues I'm seeing are the false positive S9 warning about section counts—the source genuinely has 3 sections despite the automated check flagging 6 headings—and the incomplete definition of Robustness in the knowledge file, which cuts off mid-sentence from the source material.\n\nLooking more closely at the Robustness definition, the source provides both a general definition about minimizing damage and maintaining function against various threats, and then Nablarch's specific interpretation focusing on disaster resistance and security strength. The knowledge file only captures the Nablarch-specific meaning, so including the broader definition would give a more complete picture for answering questions about this concept.\n\nFor Testabilit